description:
Two weeks after the cowardly Pahalgam Attack - while the perpetrators are still at large - action against Pakistan is becoming more evident with each passing day. However the Govt has also clamped down on any uncomfortable questions about lapses that led to Pahalgam. Is it 'too soon' to ask questions from our Govt?? What has been the BJP's track record of asking questions after a Pakistani attack- when it was in the opposition?? 
Why India needs to do BOTH - ask questions to itself and give Pakistan a befitting answer.

comments.text: On May 7 Indian Air Force targeted Pakistani civilian cites claiming to be terrorist sites through air to surface missiles, keeping its fighter jets within their borders. During this activity, Pakistan Air Force shot down at least six Indian Air Force jets including Rafael.  Afterwards, India, grounded all its fighter jets and resorted in using surface to surface missiles targeting Pakistans military installation. This was mainly to curb its humiliation for multiple jets downing, but on the other side, this increased this conflict to a critical point where Pakistan then also retaliated through its long-range surface to surface missiles that destroyed some of the Indian military installations. Afterwards international powers interceded and cease-fire was agreed. During this conflict, Indian media have been extremely biased, and propagating lies to their fellow citizens, but International media was reporting actual facts of war status between the two countries. Recent admittance by Indian top military general of Indian Air Force jets downing has created another set of debates in India on how to absorb the spilled truth, which on one side Modi supporters blaming the general and other side calling for thorough investigation.
